SIMPLE: phrygian
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Phrygian
<hw>Phryg"i*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Phrygius</ets>, Gr. <grk>Fry`gios</grk>, fr. <grk>Frygi`a</grk>
Phrygia, a country of Asia Minor.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to
Phrygia, or to its inhabitants.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Phrygian mode</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>one of the
ancient Greek modes, very bold and vehement in style; -- so called
because fabled to have been invented by the <xex>Phrygian</xex>
<persfn>Marsyas</persfn>.</cd> <au>Moore (Encyc. of Music).</au> --
<col><b>Phrygian stone</b></col>, <cd>a light, spongy stone, resembling
a pumice, -- used by the ancients in dyeing, and said to be drying and
astringent.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phrygian</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Phrygian
<hw>Phryg"i*an</hw>, <pos>prop. n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A native or
inhabitant of Phrygia.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eccl. Hist.)</fld> <def>A Montanist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phrygian cap</ent>⟦br⟧
